pr_review_body:
If I understand correctly it seems like now we're adding a new resolver that basically provides data that combines the failed + materialized statuses, but it seems like a lot of the existing materialization code is duplicated to handle the failed case as well.

I'm wondering if we can just remove the original "materializedPartitions" resolver and rely purely on the resolver created in this PR? Since it seems like in the places we want to view materialization statuses, we also want to view failed statuses.

@bengotow do you know if we need just the `materializedPartitions` resolver? One instance I can think of is to display materialization events per partition on the asset details page, but we do have a different resolver for that

Find a way to annotate experimental APIs and mark all of Tango with it.

```
@experimental
def foo():
    pass

@experimental
class Foo:
    pass
```

Looks good!

Mostly nits and one openish question to the team:

@DataDog/apm-python should this integration be named "graphql" or "graphql-core". The package/pypi name for this integration is "graphql-core" but it is used by most/all graphql libraries.

@jcarbelbide thanks for your contribution. I made few comments on your implementation.
If not done, I would suggest also a quick look at [documentation](https://pymeasure.readthedocs.io/en/latest/dev/adding_instruments.html), just to make sure nothing is missed.
I would say that also You should add yourself among the authors (files [`authors.rst`](https://github.com/pymeasure/pymeasure/blob/dfca962f2f90ee304fd765b5e90c2bb43e5e7551/docs/about/authors.rst) and [`AUTHORS.txt`](https://github.com/pymeasure/pymeasure/blob/dfca962f2f90ee304fd765b5e90c2bb43e5e7551/AUTHORS.txt)), amend file [`__init__.py`](https://github.com/pymeasure/pymeasure/blob/dfca962f2f90ee304fd765b5e90c2bb43e5e7551/pymeasure/instruments/__init__.py) and [`index.rst`](https://github.com/pymeasure/pymeasure/blob/dfca962f2f90ee304fd765b5e90c2bb43e5e7551/docs/api/instruments/index.rst)

You can also just do 

```css
span[slot="meta"] {

}
```

Nice, thanks. Things are starting to look cleaner :)

Heads-up for distro package maintainers this will need a change if you're testing the package outside of tox. I recommend only running `tests/unit` if you want to avoid the docker dependency.
@kloczek @derekschrock @svenstaro @williamh @FedericoCeratto

Thank you @anmyachev - this fix looks good, but I think we want to defer the specific computation to the query compiler - that way we support other query compilers that may not want to move data out of distributed storage, or may incur costs doing so. Would you mind making the API Layer for the Array, Series, and DF route to a query_compiler method, and have the query_compiler method just return this? We could have it look something like this maybe?
```python
def __iter__(self, lib="pandas", squeeze=False):
     return self.to_numpy().__iter__() if lib != "pandas" else (self.to_pandas().squeeze() if squeeze else self.to_pandas()).__iter__()
```

LGTM
Good catch!
@Nir-Az please change this PR to development branch.
